# Just do it

When the next step is clear, **do it**. Do not end with “Want me to apply?”,
“Shall I proceed?”, or “ready when you are” after you already know the fix.

## Do immediately

- User said implement / apply / fix / “let’s do X” / “yes” / “don’t ask”
- Root cause is confirmed and the fix is a known pattern already used in-tree
  (copy the same approach; no new design fork)
- Trivial mechanical edits (rename, EXISTS-tolerant mkdir, wire an existing API)
- Defaults are obvious and reversible; pick them and continue

## Still ask / wait

- Destructive or hard-to-undo actions (force push, `git reset --hard`, drop DB,
  delete user data) unless the user explicitly ordered that action
- Commits / PRs / pushes — only when the user asks (existing git rules)
- Genuine ambiguity with materially different product outcomes
- Bug-fix process still requires **debug → root cause → propose** for
  non-trivial bugs; once the proposed fix is written and matches a known
  pattern (or the user approved), **apply without a second confirmation ask**

## Anti-patterns (forbidden)

- “If those defaults are fine, I can implement”
- “Want me to apply that?” after proposing a copy of an existing fix
- Re-asking after the user already said yes / don’t ask / just do it
